<div class="xar-mod-body">
  <xar:template type="module" file="admin-menu" />
  <img src="#xarTplGetImage('admin_generic.gif', 'base')#" alt="official icon" width="96" height="96" class="xar-module-icon" />
  <h2>
    <xar:mlstring>Overview</xar:mlstring>
  </h2>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>What is it?</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
      <xar:mlstring>The Headlines module allows you to syndicate content from other website.  It also allows you to use predetermined hooks from Xaraya if you have them installed and activated.</xar:mlstring>
  </p>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>How to use it?</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
            <xar:mlstring>
            From the menu, you have three choices:
            </xar:mlstring>
            <ol>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Add Headlines</strong>: Add a new syndication headline for processing.</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Manage Headlines</strong>: View, edit and delete headlines that you have added to your site.
                        Add alternative titles and headlines for your feeds, and order the display of the feeds
                    </xar:mlstring>
                </li>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Modify Configuration</strong>: Update the global configuration for the module.
                         Here you can set </xar:mlstring>
                         <ul>
                           <li><xar:mlstring>the number of feeds per page</xar:mlstring></li>
                           <li><xar:mlstring>optionally select an Article module publication type to import the feed items. You will need a title and summary field in your publication type to import feed items.</xar:mlstring></li>
                           <li><xar:mlstring>choose which content to import to your selected publication type. Feed, Title, Description and an optional link to the originating feed item can also be added in your publication type summary field.
                              </xar:mlstring>
                           </ul>
                </li>
             </ol>

       </p>
        <p>
            <xar:mlstring>
            Hook the Categories module to Headlines to classify your feeds by category on display.
            </xar:mlstring>
        </p>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>Included Blocks</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
            <ul>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>RSS Block</strong> allows you to provide selected feeds in blocks on your siten and define number of items, title, and refresh times.</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Cloud Block</strong> Creates a cloud block from blog feeds, using Ping module to notify of updates and Scheduler module to update.</xar:mlstring></li>

            </ul>
       </p>
  <h3>
    <xar:mlstring>Included Hooks</xar:mlstring>
  </h3>
  <p>
            <xar:mlstring>There are no included hooks with Headlines</xar:mlstring>
  </p>
        <h3>
            <xar:mlstring>Credits</xar:mlstring>
        </h3>
      <p>
            <xar:mlstring>The RSS Block is using </xar:mlstring><a href="http://freshmeat.net/projects/phpfeedparser/?topic_id=914"> <xar:mlstring> PHP feedParser </xar:mlstring> </a><xar:mlstring> as its backend.   The notes for the feedParser by Reverend Jim are as follows</xar:mlstring>:
    </p>
    <p>
            <xar:mlstring>
            feedParser was created due to the lack of a good, flexible, class-based RSS feed parser for PHP. It has been built as a class, and currently handles RSS 0.91, RSS 0.92, RSS 0.93, RSS 1.0, and RSS 2.0 feeds. For channels it grabs the title, description, link, and creator. For items it grabs the title, description, link, and date. It also provides a form of the date converted into the local timezone to facilitate cronological sorting of items. The dates are provided in UNIX timestamp format for easy manipulation by other PHP functions. </xar:mlstring>
    </p>
        <h3><xar:mlstring>Further Information</xar:mlstring></h3>
  <p>
       <xar:mlstring>Extended information about this module can be found at </xar:mlstring><a title="#xarML('Headlines Module - Xaraya Extension 777')#" href="http://www.xaraya.com/index.php/release/777.html">Xaraya Extension and Releases</a>.
       </p>
